More Typhoid Cases Registered in Russia's Daghestan
------------------------------------------------------------------
26 Oct 1998
MOSCOW, October 26 - The number of typhoid fever cases keeps
growing in Russia's republic of Daghestan, Itar-Tass learned on Monday at the
press service of the Russian Ministry for Emergencies.
Twenty-six people, including eight children, have been hospitalized there with
typhoid symptoms, and in 21 cases the disease was confirmed. The patients'
condition is reported as satisfactory.
The source of the disease is sewage waters penetrating water-pipes. Last
Thursday 15 people, six of them children, were delivered to the Makhachkala
republican hospital for infectious diseases. Typhoid fever was confirmed in 11
cases, the Ministry for Emergencies said [then].
See Also
"Cholera has affected 26 people in the Russian Caucasus
republic of Dagestan according to Gennady Onishchenko, the first
deputy health minister" (ref. above). Did they change the
diagnosis, or is this just a coincidence? - Mod.JW
